items.name: G41 - Girls' Frontline Character LoRA
items.description:
About

I've noticed that there wasn't a LoRA of G41 from GFL and decided to give it a go. Recommended to use at weights 0.65-0.8.

All of the preview images were generated with the same prompts and nothing was done to them after the initial generation. I did leave out any inconsistent results and generally the results that didn't look amazing or close to the character, so keep that in mind, but it's fairly consistent if you use more words like: blonde, heterochromia, etc. in your prompt.

The LoRA was trained on Anything V5 and the previews were also generated using it, I've not tested it on any other models but I'm sure it will work fine on others.

Update!

Fixed several issues that were pointed out. The model should work much better now than before. I still recommend adding in prompts like: heterochromia, blonde hair, etc. but just using the g41 trigger word should get the general character concept out now.

The LoRA should also work much better on other models, I only tested 5 so there could be some that don't take it well but hopefully now it should be good.

Thanks to yakumonagi246 for pointing out the problems in the training for the LoRA, I probably would never have noticed and would've kept training them wrong otherwise.

modelVersions.name: v2.0
modelVersions.description:
Fixed captioning problem and trained on NAI model instead.

Should work much better with other models and not have as many issues. Generally retains a specific look and outfit (heterochromia is a bit inconsistent, much better results specifying eye colours) when using only the "g41" trigger word but using other words to define the outfit or general appearance should work much better in this version.

Thanks to yakumonagi246 for pointing out these errors in the LoRA, hopefully this version is much better trained.

What are these?

These are the textual inversion you'll often find on the posts of my models and LoRAs.

They are nothing special, but I've been requested multiple times to post them, so here we are :)

These have been tested a lot with my custom checkpoints:

The Inversions

Right now there are two inversions:

  • Hotify: changes a girl appearance to make it "sexier"

  • Prettify: adds makeup and change the perspective to a closeup

  • PrettyEyes: adds makeup focused on the eyes and eyelashes

  • NoBG: helps to avoid plain backgrounds when used in the negative prompt (or use it in the positive prompt if you want them).

  • NoTxt: helps to avoid text in the pictures when used in the negative prompt

  • Badpic: put this in the negative prompt to improve the quality of the picture

items.name: Ghislaine Dedoldia - Mushoku Tensei
items.description:
Important Note: Unfortunately, the images I selected won't recreate perfectly with the file I uploaded. When testing I realized I had mess up and had flip_aug turned on, which was causing the inconsistency of her eye-patch being applied. I fixed that for the uploaded version but I had already made a bunch of images I liked :(.

This Lora is for our muscle waifu, Ghislaine, from Mushoku Tensei! It was trained on animefull_final with 26 images with the usual self-pruning and tagging and a wide range of different images. I like keeping my prompts simple for the first few pictures so that you can see it without a whole bunch of mumbo jumbo. Make your pictures better than mine though!

What does it do you ask? Pretty simple for this one. Put in LORA, get out a Ghislaine. Profit.

How to use it: Lora strength for 1 if you just her in her normal form. 0.7-0.8 if blending with other clothing tags or Loras.

Also the trigger words are:

GhislaineMT - Only trigger word currently added.

green pants, bandeau (highly recommended)- For whatever reason, the LORA doesn't pop out the exact perfect outfit consistantly, so reminding it with these two tags makes the images MUCH more consistant.

Extra, Extra!: The eyepatch, even though better after disabled flip_aug, is still not perfect. The LORA doesn't get it right 100% of the time (though way better than my selected pictures) so expect some repetition on finding the right image.

Picture Descriptions:

1-3: AnythingV3 using just this Lora.

4: AnythingV3 and wearing a business outfit.

5: AnythingV3 combo'd with my released Angel Locon.

6: AnythingV3 combo'd with my in progress Brainwashing Locon.

7: AnythingV3 combo'd with my in progress Dominatrix Locon.

8-9: AnythingV3 combo'd with my in progress PetPlay Locon..

10: AnythingV3 combo'd with my in progress v2Corruption Locon.

11: AbyssOrange with just the Lora.

12: PerfectWorld using just this Lora.

What's next for this? If I can figure out how to improve the eyepatch or make it so you don't need green pants and bandeau, then that would cause a v2. Or feedback.

What's next that isn't this?

More character Loras. (Ivy from Soul Calibur 5, Heine from Combatants Will Be Dispatched, Conqueror Lilias from E7, Rozalin from Disgaea 2, Tharja from Fire Emblem, Catherine from Catherine Full Body, Miku from Idaten Deities, Kuribayashi Shino from GATE, Rin Sohma from Fruits Basket, Kasumi from P5, Ann from P5, Ikumi Mito from Food Wars, Alice Nakiri from Food Wars, Chika Fujiwara from Kaguya-sama, Lulu from FF10, Momo from My Hero, Vivy from Vivy, Dominique de Sade from Vanitas, and Dos from One Punch Man.) And maybe Wilhelm van Astrea, my favorite Re:Zero husbando or a Prinny from Disgaea.

V2's of some of the previous Loras. Specifically make them more diversely acceptable with other models and LORA's.

I also have some more quite NSFW Locon's. I decided to list them as well, so if people have preferences on which to fix up first let me know. Specifically, Brainwashing your waifu, CorruptV2, Symbiote Taking Over (imagine a venom-like symbiote taking over your waifu), being stepped on, Robotification, Petrified (I'm unsure if I should bother with this one anymore), Infection, Dominatrix (waifu becoming a dominatrix), Brainwashing Machine, Tentacles, Pillory, Masked Evil (A mask that possess' the waifu), Latex Corruption, Hourglass Figure, Combat Drone (hard to describe but basically making them a mindless sci-fi combat warrior), JAV Supervillain, and Holding a Leash.

And, uh, I want to make a few "normal" Locon's so I have an "knight-ify" your character one coming up. And a forest fairy one as well. And a officer one. And a barbarian one.

Or just give me some random suggestion or priority opinions. That works too.

items.name: Hair Style: Two face framing tendrils / sidebangs
items.description:
Hello! This is my first TI, an attempt to teach the diffuser how to generate the [two?] face-framing tendrils hair style.

This is an early release that may not be followed up upon, depending on popularity/usage/issues.

Keyword for each individual file is the "Trigger word" in the file details on the upper right hand part of this screen.

V07 info: "Photo" version is a more trained version of the "Illustration" inversion, and has a heavier application strength. If the photo version is used for illustration/anime-style checkpoints, it may start to override racial identity and facial features without further prompting. "Strong"/"Nike" version mightier than both; I selected the training strength that came JUST shy of starting to burn images on some models. About the heaviest application I can manage, for the truly stubborn checkpoints.

V07 Known issues:

  • May require a higher-strength version for higher application rate in models like Deliberate and Realistic.

  • Mediumish-strength bias towards a neutral gray background (or a majority-gray/brown/boring background even when prompted). I can't seem to drop this bias yet, sorry.

  • If it applies too strongly, it can start to affect facial details, and will definitely start to weight the hair color towards black or red. Both of these should (should..) be fairly easy to override without much extra prompting.

If you have any issues or feedback, please comment below!

Model was trained on a fairly-consistent Irish face with black hair (with attempts to de-bias the final result against both of those features afterwards) on a neutral gray background from a variety of zoom and angle shots, with varying amounts of hair contained in the "tendrils" (anywhere from a few strands to straight-up curtain bangs).

Huge thank you to BelieveDiffusion's textual inversion training tutorial located at https://github.com/BelieveDiffusion/tutorials/blob/main/consistent_character_embedding/README.md!

Thanks!

items.name: Jessica Chobot - TI embedding
items.description:
Jessica Chobot is a gamer and television personality. She got her start in the industry hosting gaming programming for IGN and Microsoft covering video games as well as attending many industry events. She currently can be seen on various programs on the discovery network of shows, including a show called Expedition X.

Aside from all that, it should be obvious that she's a very attractive lady. She looks just as good now as she always has, but I did choose the dataset based on much of the time earlier in her career (mostly only noticeable if you pay attention to the hairstyle).

There's probably going to be exactly 1, maybe 2 other people that understand the reference, but for diehard Chobot fans, I gave it a shot at recreating the picture. You know, the one that basically kicked off her entire career in the industry.

Tested with a good number of models with decent results. Mostly realistic style models. Not too many anime models, but a couple artistic oreinted ones though such as Dreamscaper, Galaxy Time Machine, and DucHaiten's models.

Trained up to 6000 steps on the base 1.5 model so it should work with most 1.5 models.

Some of the prompts in my images might have a different name than the actual filename, they were images I liked when I was running XYZ plot tests that I liked the result, all images have the same training strength as the 1.0 version of this TI.

I have made a decent number of Textual Inversions for personal use for projects, but not many that I have actually released to the public, so hopefully this is up to the mark for people's standards.

Huge shoutout to JernauGurgeh for being such a good soul and being not only helpful, but enthusiastic and a great member of the community. You should check out their work, they're one of the people I respect and look to most as a member of the community when it comes to creating good TIs and sharing good info.

items.name: Noihara Himari - Omamori Himari (TV Anime style)
items.description:
(v2.0)
Updated LoRA with a bigger dataset and trained on NAI. Should be more consistent generating images of Noihara Himari, but it can also generate other characters from the show very closely.

The trigger word for this version is promotionalart but it can work without it.

(v1.0)
I had first used SD 1.5 Pruned for training but It didn't replicate the art style that I wanted, then I decided to go with Lykon's AnyLoRA - Checkpoint (Pruned) for training which gave me just what I was looking for.

I tested mostly on AnythingV5 (works with other Anime style models) with 0.55 - 0.65 weight which gives me a very decent depiction of the character along with the art style, while also allowing some flexibility to change clothes poses and backgrounds, however since the training was done with only one image, the AI will attempt to generate something similar to the base image used for training, at anything above 0.8 weight, the AI will generate a similar pose to the base image more often while still allowing different clothing. No trigger word needed, but adding OmaHimaStyle seems to add a bit of extra detail (maybe is just extra noise, idk).
This was mainly made to generate Noihara Himari images but surprisingly It can also be used as style LoRA when combined with other models, however this LoRA sems to start breaking with school uniforms when above 0.8 weight, likely because of the base image having a school uniform idk, I just wanted something quick to try out, I'm quite impatient. Enjoy (I guess?) but it can be fixed by adding more weight to specific tags.

Basic prompt: Solo, 1girl, portrait, Black hair, purple eyes, very long hair, high ponytail, long ponytail, hair bow, pink bow, big hair, red shirt, sailor shirt, bangs, sidelocks, <lora:OmaHimaStyle:1>,

This LoRA's can generate Noihara Himari more accurately and also some of the other characters from the show.

items.description:
Created by GeomanticArts also please consider supporting the trainer at geoloras.com

I can tell, everyone is frantic, urgently waiting for someone to make a Servbot LoRA! "Please, I really want to generate Servbots, but I don't know how!" "My Servbots just look like generic robos!" Don't worry I got you fam.

Get some adorable, helpful Servbots to assist you in your images! Servbots are too kawaii to be ignored and should be applied en masse to your generations.

>_< face is tagged as such, but it's very inconsistent. It works sometimes but nowhere near as often as I'd like.

Does fine with no other terms but the 'Servbot' term. But even though the training images are all edited they do still sometimes give you a pair of Tron's stupid sexy legs next to/on top of the servbots. There are not a huge number of training images to choose from of servbots alone, nearly all of them are next to Tron Bonne. It doesn't do this -too- often, but it does happen. 'No humans' tag will pretty much guarantee this doesn't happen.

Example images all made with AOM2-7thV3_C_40 at weight 1

'servbot [mega man]' example prompt is all that's needed

LoRA metadata has all the tags used.

The trainer's twitter can be found at https://twitter.com/GeomanticArts

Trained on NAI.

items.name: Ultra Sharp High Contrast Tutorial +vae&upscaler
items.description:
If you found this useful, please click the :heart: and post your own image using the technique with a rating. Thanks!

To help with some confusion on how I get my preview images for my models, I created this tutorial. It's a really great technique for creating very sharp details and high contrast in any image with any model. Without having to upscale it even larger. (see a side by side comparison in the model images)


Step 1:
I start with a good prompt and create a batch of images. When using a Stable Diffusion (SD) 1.5 model, ALWAYS ALWAYS ALWAYS use a low initial generation resolution. The model's latent space is 512x512. If you gen higher resolutions than this, it will tile the latent space. That's why you sometimes get long necks, or double heads. However, depending on newer models, their training, and your subject matter, you can get away with 768 in some cases. But if you get strange generations and don't know what's wrong, bring your resolution withing the 512x512 zone. To get the higher resolution images, you use hires fix, explained in Step 2.
In this tutorial, I use the very superior and legendary A-Zovya RPG Artist Tools version 2 model. It's quite capable of 768 resolutions so my favorite is 512x768. Posting on civitai really does beg for portrait aspect ratios. In the image below, you see my sampler, sample steps, cfg scale, and resolution.

Additionally, I'm using the vae-ft-mse-840000-ema-pruned.ckpt for VAE and the 4x_foolhardy_Remacri.pth for my upscaler. Any upscaler should work fine, but the default latent upscalers are very soft, and the opposite of this tutorial. The vae and upscaler is included in the files of this tutorial for you to download. The VAE goes in your /stable-diffusion-webui/models/VAE folder and the upscaler goes in your /stable-diffusion-webui/models/ESRGAN folder.

Step 2:
Once I find the image I like, I put the seed number in the seed box. Like in the picture below, I leave everything the same including the initial resolution.

When you click the Hires. fix checkbox, you get more options. I choose my upscaler and upscale by 2. You can see the resize dialogue shows it will gen a 512x768 image, but then regen over that initial image to the higher resolution of 1024x1536. This gives it better details and a chance to fix things it couldn't do in smaller resolutions, like faces and eyes.
Then I select a denoising strength. The range is from 0 to 1. The smaller the number, the closer it will stay with the original generation. A higher number will allow it to make up more details which can fix things, and sometimes break things. So adjust the slider to your preference. I usually go from 0.25 to as high as 0.5. Any higher than that, I probably didn't like the original generation to begin with and now I'm going to get something wildly different.

Step 3:
Your image will show up in the box to the right as usual. Click on the "send to img2img" box as shown below.

Once you're on the img2img page, make sure your prompt is exactly the same. Make sure all other settings are exactly the same also. It will sometimes give you a different sampler and CFG scale.

Make sure you have selected "just resize", the same settings from the previous image including the seed number. The ONLY difference here will be the resolution, it should be the larger size you hires fixed to, and the denoising strength. Most video cards can handle this in img2img. If you get vram errors, try using --xformers and/or --no-half in your startup script. For extreme cases, you could also use --medvram. Otherwise, a weaker card will just take more time than a more powerful one, but at this point, you're giving final polish to a good cherry-picked image.
Denoising strength: the higher this number, the more contrast and sharpness will be added. Too low and you'll see no difference. To high and it will shred the image into confetti. This number will vary from image, subject matter, details and even the model you use. For my use, I get good results from 0.12 to 0.35.

And that's it, PLEASE PLEASE PLEASE post some ultra sharp images you made and rank this tutorial. Feedback and encouragement is what fuels creators to make more and post their stuff. Support those that you like.

Obligatory donation chant:
Do you have requests? I've been putting in many more hours lately with this. That's my problem, not yours. But if you'd like to tip me, buy me a beer. Beer encourages me to ignore work and make AI models instead. Tip and make a request. I'll give it a shot if I can. Here at Ko-Fi
